– 2 –
12 entitled, including any future compensation, to be reduced by the additional amount
13 paid by the employer. Existing law provides that the industrial insurer or
14 Administrator of the Division of Industrial Relations of the Department of Business
15 and Industry has a lien against the total amount paid by the employer.
16 (NRS 616C.215)
17 If the injury of an injured employee was caused under circumstances creating
18 legal liability in a person other than the employer or a person in the same employ,
19 or entitling the employee or the dependents of the employee to receive proceeds
20 under his or her employer’s policy of uninsured or underinsured vehicle coverage,
21 existing law authorizes an injured employee or the dependents of the employee,
22 under certain circumstances, to take proceedings to recover damages from that third
23 party or to recover those proceeds under the policy. Existing law also authorizes the
24 industrial insurer or Administrator, under certain circumstances, to recover
25 damages from that third party or recover proceeds under the policy. Additionally,
26 under existing law, the industrial insurer or Administrator has a lien against the
27 total proceeds of any recovery by the injured employee or the dependents of the
28 employee. Existing law requires the amount of compensation to which the injured
29 employee or the dependents of the employee are entitled, including any future
30 compensation, to be reduced by the amount of damages or proceeds recovered.
31 (NRS 616C.215)
32 This bill limits the reduction of compensation, including future compensation,
33 to a reduction based on the portion of any amount paid or the portion of damages or
34 proceeds recovered which represents economic damages. This bill also provides
35 that the industrial insurer or Administrator only has a lien upon the portion of any
36 amount paid or the portion of any judgment, settlement or otherwise which
37 represents economic damages, instead of the total amount paid or the total proceeds
38 of any recovery. This bill defines the term “economic damages,” in accordance
39 with provisions of existing law, to mean damages for medical treatment, care or
40 custody, loss of earnings and loss of earning capacity. (NRS 41A.007)
41 This bill provides that the injured employee or the dependents of the employee
42 are entitled to be made whole for the injury, and a lien amount is recoverable only
43 if the injured employee or the dependents of the employee have been made whole.
44 This bill: (1) requires adjustment of the lien amount to reflect a proportional share
45 of any expenses incurred by the injured employee or the dependents of the
46 employee in procuring the payment or recovery; (2) limits the lien amount to the
47 compensation received by the injured employee or dependents of the employee; and
48 (3) excludes from the lien the amount of any benefit penalty or certain other
49 administrative fines.
50 Existing law requires an injured employee or the dependents of the employee,
51 or the attorney or representative of the injured employee or the dependents, to
52 notify the industrial insurer or the Administrator in writing before initiating certain
53 proceedings or actions. (NRS 616C.215) This bill removes that requirement.
54 Existing law generally provides that an action to recover damages for an injury or
55 death of a person must be commenced within 2 years. (NRS 11.190) This bill
56 prohibits an industrial insurer or the Administrator from initiating certain
57 proceedings or actions against a person other than the employer or a person in the
58 same employ unless the injured employee or the dependents of the employee has
59 not initiated a proceeding or action within 1 year of the date on which the injury
60 occurred. If the industrial insurer or Administrator initiates such a proceeding or
61 action, this bill: (1) requires the industrial insurer or the Administrator to
62 immediately notify the injured employee or the dependents of the employee, or an
63 attorney or representative of the injured employee or the dependents, of the
64 proceeding or action in writing; and (2) entitles the injured employee or the
65 dependents of the employee to intervene in the proceeding or action.
